segments.text: visiting with the students, which I guess was important to the students, being straight from practice.
So it would relate to them about what they intended to do.
Because historically, 90% of our graduates here and throughout the nation have gone into practice.
And I think try as hard as they might, that's not going to change a whole lot.
I hope it doesn't anyway.
But I don't know.
The difference in that philosophy I'm sure has come out.
Do both of you think that it's important for faculty in the college to have had a practical experience in the field?
Well, I'd say it's an advantage.
I don't know how important it is, but perhaps so.
Because the students are pretty quick to detect if you're telling them a story, stringing them along with the book version, or whether you've been there.
Do you find this to be true?
Well, yeah.
I think so.
They respect you for having been there.
Yeah.
Do you think they're better able to sit and wait on the job?
And I think the students are surprisingly capable of doing that.
They've always been there.
Are most of our faculty, have they had some experience and practice?
Well, I've been away from it as long as it takes.
I'd say most of them, it's a minimal amount of experience.
Typically, your engineers and certainly your historians don't practice anyway, I guess.
But academic people don't really know the real world out there.
And I think that's kind of interesting
The practice that most of our clinic faculty has had has been in an academic environment where they are associating with specialists instead of seeing a general practice.
Most of our faculty are coming from the intern residency program, from clinics.
It's still a controlled kind of a laboratory environment.
Well, you don't have to deal with the economics of it.
Yeah, right.
And that's a big, that's a key difference.
Yeah.
Probably not a plan to go into practice.
You have to shoot from the hip more.
You don't have all the laboratory facilities and diagnostics, sophisticated instruments.
Yeah, diagnostics.
That's a good point.
Yeah, I would think that would be something that's very different in the environment.
I know my dad, he was a county agent type and all that.
And then in the implement business, he always talked about the sterile environment of academics.
They just didn't know.
I think that's important.
I don't think there's any question about our faculty now is better qualified to teach than I was.
Technicians are good.
But I think that it has some problems that we need to be aware of educating these kids.
I don't know if this is a fair question, but let me come back.
Since both of you have been through the same experience, what did you do with your practice finally?
Did you sell it?
Did you turn over a partner?
Was there anything to sell?
I don't need money, but I just... My associate had been with me for about nearly four years, I guess, on a percentage of the...
net income.
But about first of the year, first of 71, I'd made him a 50-50 partner.
But I continued to own the real estate, just leased him, leased the partnership, the real estate.
And I guess the wisdom of the attorney that drew up the papers, he said, any time you get into a legal arrangement like this, like a partnership,
that is the time to plan how to dispose of the partnership.
You have good feelings toward each other, you're amicable, and you're rationally discussing things, and you need to plan a way out of a partnership when you go into the partnership.
And this served to be, I think, to the advantage of both of us, eventually.

But when I came up here then and decided to come and went back and discussed it with my partner, we arranged again with an attorney that if I didn't return to the practice within a period of three years, he was to buy the other half of my practice.
And we set out the terms and the purchase price and all of that at the time.
Just to say I didn't return in three years.
And at the time it was a very attractive opportunity for him.
Oh, no doubt, no doubt.
He's made a better businessman out of a deal than I ever did when I was in practice.
It's been a very lucrative practice for him.
I don't know whether they've done it more practice than they did when I was in practice,
Give me more dollars.
Veterinary medicine has improved the economics of it, for one thing.
It was good for both of us, as it turns out.
What did you do, Charlie?
Well, I had a young man who came when he graduated, came to work for me, but he didn't put in the hour and time required.
He went to work in the regulatory.
I remained by myself for 16 and a half years the rest of the time.
I don't think you can sell even good will.
Sometimes you can leave good image and move in.
But your physical plant and your actual inventory is about... That's what you got.
If a guy's very smart, you can sell him a big deal and make him believe it because you got a lot of money made.
When I went into practice, I had no money.
I just bought a car and that was it.
And I would order two bottles of, for instance, calcium gluconate from Jack Miller, another veterinary supplier.
They'd put it on the Greyhound bus and get it in an hour and a half.
And when I used one, I ordered one more until I built up the inventory.
I rented a building that had a 14-foot ceiling, was 60 feet wide and about 440 feet long on the main track, Main Street.
And people weren't used to small animal parks.
They had two
quacks in the area there, non-graduate, non-licensed, you know, shot givers, and stayed busy all the time, cleaning cows, pulling calves, that sort of thing.
And it was, I'd sit there three days, wouldn't make a call, you know, just a matter of trying to weather the storm without a level.
A guy would come in with his wife's dog, and he'd get out and stand on the, we were next to the bank.
He'd stand on the street a while, look both ways, if he didn't see any of his friends, he'd go out and get the dog, put it in his coat, and bring it inside, you know.

And I had one cage, and when I was in Houston, I had a desire to set up a practice, and I had rented an office, and off hours and weekends, I would operate, you know, kind of a diagnostic skin treatment sort of thing there on Harvard, at the corner of White Oak Drive and Harvard over in the Heights.
And I moved that cage and that table, examination table, which had been with the surgery table, I moved that with me.
And in due time, we picked up one, so we lost the rent of that building and we moved to a corner of a service station sort of thing.
And most of the work was done in a field.
90% of it was probably lower down in the field.
Got enough money together, I bought a place that bettered land board and then I sold that
a little ranch type deal and built a clinic.
The name of it was the Near the Nothing Ranch.
It was a brand registered in Hill County.
Had her raise her cattle along and built a clinic and that was quite an improvement.
You treat three while you're treating one in the country.
I guess the best thing that happened was the advent of the four-wheel drive vehicle, which I purchased an old army jeep and fixed that thing up and then I wore that one out in another one.
and then got into the pickup, the kept sort of thing.
And when I left, there was, I came down here, one of the seniors, graduating seniors, bought the place, and bought a home.
His wife knew nothing about their medicines.
He had no help, but eventually he gave the thing up, and I got it back.
I sold it to him.
It was an automobile, so I had to reclaim it with all your feelings.
Then I leased the clinic facility and it turned into something else.
So you basically dissolved the practice and sold the facilities and so forth.
Well, there's another veterinarian who lived there in town.
He also is Dr. Maddox who heads the meat inspection training school at the feds there in Fort Worth and has for about 30 years.
Rick started in doing some practice.
He built him a little surgery room, whatever, in his backyard and did some small animal practice and a little large animal practice, but he was gone, you know, all day, so it was a matter of night.
That pretty soon got over.
But there were no veterinarians.
There were two veterinarians in Hillsboro.
Dr. Ralph George came there just before I came here.
And there were about five in Cleveland.
So they sort of sorted the area.
We got to walk to Hatchie, Dr. Kelly, and Dr. Wheaton.
And I had a 10-mile equidistant to all the small towns from Grandview, Taska, Albany, and Lake Pearl, Cutler.
Far down is Whitney and as far up is Fort Worth.
We got some equine practice out of Fort Worth.
And your business is basically calls.
Yes, they don't bring them into you.
You go.
Oh, yeah, I forgot the clinic.
They brought me in.
Okay, I can get out work.
We did with record outpatient for pregnancy diagnoses That sort of thing that man mood a thousand cows 55 bulls in there from Montana.
He got tired the cold weather and It was sort of a dormant type branch operation has been there all the time They had a few sheep when this guy came in and

images began to change the charlotte people began to move in the exotics we then provided facility for that i availed myself of the high school kiddos by putting putting a tv in the reception room and let them play 42. no card no whiskey no drinking no beer but let them watch tv and play it out and i always had somebody for the night work at the clinic yeah and uh
The night watchman checked the thing, and he'd drive in and shine the lights out there.
We had a small paddock we kept the potential cavers in, which they looked like they were going to calve at night.
By 4 o'clock, we'd do a section and be good to go in about a minute.
It worked out real good.
I had a daytime receptionist, and I had a day man who went with me on calls and worked in the clinic.
Then I had a night man, and then I had a Saturday and Sunday person.
I had four late people.
And I was doing work.
That's when I decided.
I had two children.
They were asleep when I got home.
They were asleep when I left in the mornings.
So I said, we've got to do something else, you know.
And I decided, well, here I've been 30 straight days and nights, no time off, weekends and all.
And about four other people are keeping up with what I'm doing.
So I decided to look for something else.
And I went to Houston and talked with a classmate, Dr. Myatt.
His partner had left.
He said, oh, we have a
two days a week when they're playing together, you have, well, every other weekend, all that, you know.
And I said, well, who does emergency calls at night, fractures and that sort of thing?
He said, well, Leland's been doing those.
And I said, well, uh-huh.
Boyd's fixing to get that.
If I want to do that, I want to stay home and get all the money.
I'm not going to split.
So that's what, and I looked for something the other day.
That, and I came here to the university.
But you had a single practice, I mean, you were the sole...
Single person practice, general practice, we did everything.
That's not common now, is it?
Or is it?
Well, there's too much knowledge and too much specialty work, there's too much liability to try to do all those things by yourself.
Yeah.
And I don't think, those who do it are in East Texas areas like Melvin Ketchum and somebody like that.
Yeah.
Small communities.
It can be done.
You can learn, as Elmer said a while ago, to give you an eyeball diagnosis.
You don't have to take a computerized printout sheet with the norms and the actuals and go down to the checklist and say, well, it must be this or this.
You can still make a successful practice.
When you're going over treatment, 70% are going to get well anyway if you just handle it right.
And you have to be able to deal with the other part of it, the necropsies.

The thing that amazed me when I came here was that I can remember as a student we had one glass syringe and someone broke it so they had to get on a bicycle and come to the north gate and buy another one and go back and boil it in the old sterilizer before we could continue.
When I came here I didn't find it a hell of a lot different.
They had one instrument cabinet, they had one surgery pack, and you did surgery on the horse, you had to clean it up and autoclave it before you could do the next procedure.
And when I made any calls to the dairy for the university or whatever, I still had my pickup with the cover deal on the back and the instruments in it.
And I'd just load the students up and we'd go with my stuff, check out stuff out of the pharmacy and go to it.
And then we got a little more money and I prevailed upon Dr. Callahan that we need this and we need that.
How would you, again this is really random, what would you say would be the high and low points of your practice when you were practicing?
Low point from 1955-56.
We had a drought area up there and I had clients who were buying and selling cattle and horses and
and this sort of thing, and those who were operating on annual loans from the bank, they went under.
The lots where the cattle had been had sunflowers six feet tall in them, no cattle.
They owed me and my workmate, I guess, $12,000 at one time receivable.
I had $156 in the bank at the time I paid all these drug bills, and I should have known, but I didn't.
You were out of business, huh?
And so, you know, we weathered the storm.
We paid our bills.
We tightened our belts.

57 it started to rain things started to pick up this guy moved in these animals i bought an electro ejaculator for semen evaluation people you know had one or two bulls and they said well you know you don't get bread i'll sell them buy some more cows buy another bull if they go ahead and when i got the the setup with the scope and uh had a deal to go out the the angus man had 55 bulls and had me test all 55 bulls for semen evaluation
And these other guys said, well, hell, I guess old Ashton and Mastin could afford to do that.
I'll check my one book on it if there's something wrong.
So, you know, things started snowballing.
Do you think, I remember that, Joe, I was in the school in Texas in 55, 56, but was that pretty pervasive all over the state?
You think that most veterinarians went through that same kind of, maybe not in East Texas, but in the west of it all?
No, we did.
And I remember that was a terrible...
My low point, though, came just a little bit before that, about 1953, I guess.
Of course, the drought didn't affect us right in the immediate Rio Grande Valley.
Yeah, because you've got the water and the irrigation area and such as that.
But the economy was depressed because of the drought throughout Texas, and it affected our practice in that respect.
But in 51 I took in my first partner.
That was two years after I'd opened.
I took in a partner who was a classmate of mine and he'd been down in Mexico on the Aftosia program, the foot and mouth disease program.
Been about a year down there and he came back up to
and built a clinic.
While his clinic was being built, he was coming up to West Laco and just spending each day with me just trying to get his hands back into practice, Tom Mosley.
And I taught the world and all of them while we were in class together and school together as well as after graduation.
And things were going so well for us at that time that even after he got his clinic finished, he continued to

work with me and we might i made a partner out of it not in the real estate but yeah 50 50 net income in the practice and that was went on for two years i guess he was sitting with a brand new completed veterinary clinic in harlingen commuting back and forth to hardington and practicing with me but they got so slow and quiet that we decided we'd better split up and him make a
run at it and hardly continue to investigate.
And that was really the low point, I guess, to have to turn loose a partner that I've known an awful lot of.
We were just extremely compatible and enjoyed each other's companionship as well as sharing our...
But you were just really having trouble surviving.
That's right.
It was just...
Well, that's kind of nature, I guess, of any business, really, if you think about it.
It's not just peculiar to veterinary practice or anything.
In fact, then, it was about 1956 that I took in my second partner who was with me for nine years at that time.
They built Falcon Dam at the time.
They were expecting it to take several years for the dam to be built.
But they had one of the hurricanes come in that dumped

very little water on the coast but came in up up river and there's water in the watershed up the river and san juan river and phil falcon lake and one rain yeah i mean i think i remember that kind of turn the economy of the valley around when they had the constant water how much time did both of you have to spend actually with business affairs in your practice
Managing the books.
Did you have, did you hire accountants?
How'd you do that?
Or did you do it yourself?
We had no business experience.
I didn't before I went in, you know.
I hadn't ever had any money in my life anyway, and $100 a month seemed like a hell of a bunch.
Working there in Houston, I was able to get some exposure working at the packing house.
But we had a hist account book system, and my wife worked at the clinic for the first, in the office for the first, oh golly, eight years, I think.
So she was your receptionist, bookkeeper, basically.
Bookkeeper, telephone person, dog baler, cage cleaner, and everything.
We just did whatever it had to do to make it go.

his account system was one that was a commercial thing they put out day by day thing and of course there was a person who did income tax returns we didn't have to worry about that for five years you know sort of an in-house operation again the drug salesman would come by or the bill reed people from drug out come by and check the farmers here ask you what you need did you rely on them quite a bit for your for your uh information on medications etc
Yeah, new drugs and flyers, briefs, prices, volume discounts.
You know, if you bought so much paid cash, you got 6% off.
Just about the charges while I go, or fees, like Elmo, somebody going and borrowing money at the bank at 4% then was a pretty good deal.
And they paid $5,000 or something.
I said, look, you know, this animal's about to die.
If I'm going to give you that animal back, 4% of the...
First, the price is not too high, but it didn't always amount to that.
There were other people, I guess I gave away a brick home at one time by the time I moved here by not charging 4-H club members, vocation ag dealers, that sort of thing, just doing the work for them.
Usually folks had something in return.
So it was a good thing.

When I went to the Valley to start practice, I think this is an indication of the transition that veterinary medicine made, probably as a result of World War II and its effect on the overall economy as well as on the veterinary profession.
I wanted to build a building for a veterinary hospital.
That's something that wasn't very frequently done at that time.
Most veterinary clinics moved into
an abandoned service station.
It had an excellent location.
That's where the traffic was.
It had a lot of water supply, and they had a lot of concrete, all that sort of thing.
But my dad, well, he loaned me the money.
There was no paperwork.
I couldn't show that I owed the money for the lot that I bought.
I paid $2,500 for a 50-foot lot.
$50 a book and $2,500 for the lot where I could borrow money to build a building.
The lot had to be terrible.
Well, I drew plans for a hospital and I took it to the savings and loan and tried to borrow money on it.
They weren't about to loan money for a veterinary hospital.
And, of course, they had no confidence in veterinarians.
They had nothing to do with the building.
If I didn't make a go of it, what did the savings alone do for the veterinary hospital?
So they sent me back to redraw my plans.
I had to draw plans for a residence.
Well, nobody was going to believe where I was going to build this hospital.
It was right on the main highway.
on a narrow, long, 50-foot lot.
So I had to renew my plan so it would pass as a residence.
But this day and time... Then you got the money.
I got the money.
Ten thousand dollars.
And I built the building and had money left over to buy drug stock and a surgery table.
That's what I started with and got three pieces of furniture for a reception room.
But this day and time and for the last probably 30 years, you could take your license
go into a community and go in and borrow money just on your license to practice or diploma.
That's good.
That's an indication of recognition of how the profession is recognized by the society and the banking community and everybody else.
At one time, was it IRS that considered veterinarian the same as plumbers?
And bartenders.
Plumbers and bartenders?
And what about your business?
How did you operate the business side of it?
The business side of it?
Well, I had a little bit of exposure to the business aspect of veterinary medicine with my uncle when I was practicing with him.
At that time, most veterinarians, most graduates did go out and set up their own practice unless they were going into the service.
of it anymore, that's a rare thing.
You might have maybe two or three kids out of this graduating class that's planning on moving into their own practice immediately.
They've got to go through a training period and then go to practice for a period of at least a year, maybe two or three.
The histocount bookkeeping system that Claudia referred to, of course I didn't have one in practice until 49, and first year I just kept it in a notebook, my income.

I had an Aggie friend that was a CPA in the West Licole community, and took my books to him, such as they were, and he made considerable corrections on them for another year, and then about that time histocount system came out, which was
I still consider that an excellent training for bookkeeping.
It had your daily records of both income and expenditures and then a monthly summary sheet and then the annual summary sheet that just all worked out very well.
I used that for probably 15 of the years that I was, 22 years that I was in practice, I guess.
It's still in use, I guess, isn't it, Charlie?
Except most of them operate on a computerized basis.
Oh, yeah.
I guess I overlooked one year there that was about the same as 5596.
Daughter fell off a swing set and broke her leg.
Next week, my wife said she was pregnant, and the IRS sent me a notice saying we're going to audit.
Boy, boy, boy.
When it hits, it hits hard.
I'm going to audit it one time.
There's a good experience, you know.
When it hit, it hit.
Okay, I know about your low side.
What are the high points of your, and I'll close it down in just a little bit.
I'm in no rush.
Okay.
You want to take a break?
My students need me.
They're receiving hours.
Okay.
And they, three of them did this last week, so they know very well how to do it this week.
And if they need me, they can get me on the paper.
Okay.
So just take your time.
But what were the higher points of your practice?
Time.
And then what I want to ask you is sort of compare, a general comparison of your, of the academic side, the practice side.
how you feel about veterinary medicine and veterinarians and where the profession's going and that kind of thing will wind it up pretty much at that level.
But what were the high points now?
I guess the high point was building the clinic and building the house.
We bought a lot and built a home and a VA loan and built the clinic when I sold the little farm operation we had.
Getting that together where we could work in the inside.
enjoy that a lot more.

Well that that was that was a high point of my practice is when I bought the furniture showroom shops and converted it into a veterinary clinic and until that time I didn't have any large ambulance services.
I did it on ambulatory work and all the work in the field.
Did you did you both kind of feel that throughout your practice that you sort of had the
I don't know, you've got the esteem, the respect, or whatever the community around you, people, life, veterinarians.
Is that an overstatement?
I think so.
I kind of said, yeah.
The last veterinarian that the licensed practitioner had been there was, oh golly, it must have been 1916 or 1918.
I believe the guy's name was Chris when he died of man's rats.
But they had a great deal of respect for Dr. Burns there again.
He was an outstanding individual in the community as a veterinarian.
Do you feel that veterinarians have pretty well preserved that sense of identification with the community or supportive base?
Well, I don't think practitioners are as much community-related now as they were when...
It's so much of an urban society now.
Okay, so you lose some of that personal identification.
That's right, and they're just not as involved as much in community activities as they were.
I've noticed this in
I think this is one of the most dramatic things that I noticed when I was on the selection committee.
Interviewing these kids, you ask them about how they would like to participate in community life when they're a veterinarian.
And they're all coming from Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, San Antonio, Austin.
The big cities are not coming from these smaller communities where their dad or mother had an opportunity to serve on the school board, on the city council, and such as that.
They just don't make that connection that you have the opportunity as a professional individual to participate in community activities or fairs like that.
Have you noticed that, Charlie?
Well, there's some reluctance.
For some reason, they either participate in fun runs or jobs or clubs or something like that, but they don't seem to want to participate at the city council level or the school board.
Yeah, or even the socials are community activity clubs.
Rotary club or Lions Club, Kiwanis, you know, they don't, well, I didn't hear any talk about it.
It's a different breed.
Well, it doesn't make, they can't see it as making money for them.
Yeah.
And I think, well, I think all of society now is more concerned about the dollars than they were.
Oh, I think so.
Well, I sure do.
I sure do.
What I want to kind of ask, though, relating to this general idea is, how do you think the, um,
the profile of the veterinarian has changed in the public mind as compared to the profile of the medical doctor.
Because I see a rather large change in the way the public views the medical profession and less a change in the way the public views veterinarians.
In other words, I think that the veterinarian still has, in a sense, a great deal of a sense of public affection, maybe.
That's the wrong word, but that's the idea I want to get to.
Whereas the doctor has become such a specialized and more impersonal character.
Is that wrong?
Well, it depends, though.
I think, again, on the individual.
Alcohol and drugs have taken a toll on both the veterinary profession and the medical profession.
Yeah, I saw an article about that recently.
I hadn't even really realized that veterinarians were so susceptible to that problem, but apparently they are.
My first experience in practice, and that's about two years after I got there, was an EMD who had gotten on drugs, came and gave me a check to go buy drugs.
I didn't know this until I got a check in England.
But the veterinarians, the image the veterinarians have had is, of course, earlier you have to live now.
Microchippers, snub dippers, whiskey drinkers, you know, hail raisers in general.

yeah and uh i think we've been able to live that down i'm particularly proud of the female contingent of their medicine they dress well they groom themselves well they're not addicted to drugs and alcohol in my knowledge we've had some male members of the profession but the idea of professionalism i think it uh
that everyone wants to contribute to raising the image.

The thing that's bad is, like it is with the news media, the press got on this deal in Houston where the city council passed the licensing deal, and the veterinarians have to report the names of all who had their dogs vaccinated.
You get involved with the news media, and then the veterinary profession gets the bad ball on the thing.
The same thing with the old boy that had the 42 dogs they picked up the other day.
Again, this morning in the Houston Chronicle.
You'd think that the veterinarian
Tom Durrell was the one, you know, Tom owned Pasadena, was on Shaver, you know, when Mombardi was there.

Tom's involved with it, and not really because he just knew the guy, but here's the veterinarian, he gets the fall, you know, so you have to be continually defending the profession and yourself and Leo's to such an extent that it will upgrade instead of that.
Now, I picked up from Billy Tremere and some of the group over in San Antonio the sense that maybe the professionalism
or the symbols of the profession, at least, are getting lost a little bit in this newer generation.
Dress, deportment, attire.
Oh, yeah.
I think we've seen the whole circle, Henry.
Let's go back to our executive secretary.
When we graduated, Eddie Grist, have you met him yet?
No.
Have you been told about him?
Not really.
He's an invalid now in a wheelchair confined to a wheelchair.
And he was in New Braunfels.
New Braunfels, okay.
And was extension veterinarian for when we were in school.
And then he went into practice in New Braunfels and was the secretary for the TVMA.
And at the time Eddie was secretary for the TVMA, dues were a dollar.
Yeah.

I remember the first TVMA meeting I went to was in San Antonio, and they had their business meeting, and then he kind of made the announcement that we were dismissed, and, oh, by the way, dues are a dollar.
If you go out the door, we'll leave you a dollar.
Yeah.
A dollar.
A dollar.
Yeah.
I think I copied some of the list.
We went then from Eddie Grist as secretary of TVMA, and our first meeting,

full-time executive secretary was paul blunt who was a veterinarian he was also an attorney and he was first a part-time executive secretary for the bear county veterinary association i'm surprised they didn't put you in on this i probably have that yeah i probably didn't have any records but uh
Brown and Parker didn't.
Were they present?
R.D.
Brown?
No, both of them in the hospital that day.
Is that right?
Yes, sir.
You've got to get those guys.
Yeah, they said I should come back for them.
They were partners.
It was scheduled, and they both were in the hospital.
They were two of the people in attendance at Bexar County meetings when I attended down there.
Two of those people were.
And Culpepper, their other partner.
But Paul Blunt, then, was our first full-time executive secretary.
And old Paul Blunt was poisoning with tobacco smoke.
He'd get it right in your face, and he'd take a big, deep breath, and inhale it, and the whole time he was talking, just puffing this smoke right out in your face.
And you'd be backing up to get out of it, and he'd be advancing.
But he said, when he became executive secretary, he said, I'm going to take this profession out of cowboy boots and blue jeans and put them in coats and ties.
And he did a pretty doggone good job of it.
And that went on for, well, after Paul Blunt, we had Paul.
He was the executive secretary when I was president.
That's a good quote.
I'm going to use that one.
He wore the black leather jacket you're talking about?
Oh, well, he was the PR man from Dallas.
His name was Paul.

Back to my clinic that built, my first one that I built in, turned it down to what turned out to be downtown Wesley Cove.
When I moved out to the new clinic that I remodeled the furniture store,
It turned into a fried chicken place.
Is that right?
They didn't make a go of it.
In fact, they had a little fire in it.
I don't know whether it was an insurance fire or not.
It didn't do a whole lot of damage to the building, but it was vacant for a while and I sold it to a convenience store owner that was right next door to it.
And then he eventually sold it to
a medical doctor who was an Indian doctor, not an American Indian, an orthopedic surgeon, and his wife was also a doctor, and she was an obstetrician and gynecologist.

And they took that little old brick building, 34 by 34 was the building I started off with, and I added on to it a kennel building in the back that was better constructed than the original building was, running it for $8,500.
You can imagine it wasn't a whole lot of a building.
But those people, between the two of them, just about own half of Westaco now.
Is that right?

It's amazing what those people have done.
The front was small animals and the large animal operating room was in the center and then the stable area in the other part.

And I wore coveralls for the large animal work and I'd slip those off and slip on at least from the forward linen and towel supply three-quarter length white wraparound jackets and a white shirt and black bow tie.

You small animal things, if you cover off, go out the back, you know.

put it in there and close the lid and shut it out of sight.

Is it true, incidentally, that the practice had, but it doesn't seem to be necessarily what I've gotten from you, that instead of you going to your clients, the clients are now coming to the veterinarian?

And I know you were mentioning on the phone, the automobile really revolutionized the veterinary practice business as much as anything in the world.
I had that Jeep, and I had a roll bar on it, and I had a metal cab built in, and I had a water tank on the back with a faucet on it, and all those things.
When I couldn't drive up within 10 or 20 feet of the patient,
I was pretty perplexed.
I've been to places where the creek bank was so steep that I'd be afraid to drive up and come back, so I'd back up the thing.
I wanted to take the poleaxe and cut the bigger ones down.
I'd drive over the little ones, you know, and get up to them.
It was just there in sections in the field.
Those things worked very well.
We had mud roads.

You couldn't get through that many.
Yes.
